  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscription for the Hall of Wild Cinnamon
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    This hall was once the private residence of Maritime Commander Lu, and a wild cinnamon tree grew in its courtyard. I remember seeing it when it was no thicker than a fist. After the residence fell into ruin, a military encampment was built upon the land. In the year jiaxu, when I was exiled to Hepu, I found the cinnamon tree had grown magnificently—large enough to shelter an ox beneath its canopy. It was early summer; verdant shade covered the ground, and cool breezes caressed all who passed. When rain fell, the tree whispered; when wind blew, it sang. Mountain birds and wild fowl nested in its branches, their songs as harmonious as any bronze bell or stringed instrument. Zhuangzi tells us that one who dwells in an empty valley finds joy even in the sound of footsteps. How much more reason to delight, then, when heaven and earth stir their vital breath, when all things animate and inert naturally resound with their own music? I made my dwelling in the western hall, and scarcely a moment passed when I did not lean upon my staff and tread softly beneath the tree's embrace, chanting aloud and whistling softly, wandering free and unbound. Through this cinnamon's blessing, I cultivated my spirit and nurtured my nature, and both sorrow and joy dissolved into forgetting. Moved by gratitude, I offer this inscription:

    *The cinnamon bears solitary fragrance in autumn's fading light—*
    *The very sign of virtue, and of grace.*
    *Its excellence abundantly shines forth,*
    *Perfect adornment for this hall.*
    *Beloved, I would spare it injury,*
    *Like the sweet apricot tree that the Duke of Shao once sheltered.*
    *Guard it well and never forget:*
    *May it bestow eternal splendor upon this place.*
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'year jiaxu' refers to 1394 CE in the traditional sexagenary cycle.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Zhuangzi reflects the author's philosophical temperament and suggests he found solace in natural seclusion during his exile.
  - key: ''
    value: The allusion to the 'sweet apricot tree' (甘棠) of the Duke of Shao recalls a classical image of benevolent governance; the tree was preserved by grateful subjects and became a symbol of virtuous rule and protection.
